releases.body:

- added y-axis log scale in addition to linear scale

releases.name: v2.2.0
releases.body: safety-results-over-time v2.2.0 adds a settings schema, a data-driven visit order, and a control to display and hide uncsheduled visits.  The full list of issues is available [here](https://github.com/RhoInc/safety-results-over-time/issues?q=is%3Aissue+milestone%3Av2.2.0).

releases.name: v2.1.0
releases.body: v2.1.0 adds a new control that controls the extent of the y-axis.  This control affects the visible y-axis domain but does not actually filter the data.  Additionally violin plots no longer display a singular shade of gray but color according to the group they represent.

releases.body:
Documentation update only. No code changes made.

![2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/31038805/34171941-3c9b60f4-e4be-11e7-8098-6f12d331fc7c.PNG)

releases.name: v2.0.3
releases.body:
- Improved sizing for mean circles. #31 
- Better logic when dropping non-numeric output #34

releases.name: v2.0.2
releases.body: Fix a bug that could cause duplicate controls in certain frameworks #32.

releases.name: v2.0.1
releases.body: Minor update so that filters with 0 or 1 levels no longer render. (#26)

releases.name: v2.0.0
releases.body: Version 2.0.0 of the Safety Results Over Time chart represents a major refactor, and includes many bug fixes and performance improvements. The overall framework using [webcharts-boilerplate](https://github.com/RhoInc/webcharts-wrapper-boilerplate) is still in place, but the secondary build creating a react framework has been removed, and several [configuration options](https://github.com/RhoInc/safety-results-over-time/wiki/Configuration) have been simplified, breaking backwards compatibility. A full list of resolved issues is available [here](https://github.com/RhoInc/safety-results-over-time/milestone/1?closed=1).

releases.name: v1.2.1
releases.body: Bug fix for repeated values in group control using chartfoundry renderer

This release includes: 
- The library has been refactored according to the process described in the [Webcharts Boilerplate](https://github.com/RhoInc/webcharts-wrapper-boilerplate) library. 
- A wiki has been added with details regarding chart configuration, links to examples and data guidelines.

releases.name: v1.1.0
releases.body:
- Added optional violin plot overlays
- Users can now toggle both violin plots and box plots on and off. 
- Added option to rotate x-axis ticks
This is the initial release of the Test Results Over Time tool. This interactive box and whisker plot displays lab and vital sign information at different time points.

issues.title: Improve log tick rounding.
issues.body:
Per @bzkrouse - for instance a log y-axis tick range of `[11.5, 12.3, 13, 13.699999999999996, 14.6]` yields this set of tick labels: `[12, missing, 13, 14, 15]`.  It's not obvious why the tick labels and the values in the chart differ.

The linear set of tick labels in this example is `[10,11,12,13,14,15,16,17]`.

issues.title: Add an Overall bar
issues.body: This issue is to accomplish what Jack wanted in the [Safety Histogram issue](https://github.com/RhoInc/safety-histogram/issues/9).

issues.title: Add an average for outlier explorer events on the same day
issues.body:
Request from Jack:

Jack would like an x-axis control like we have on the Outlier Explorer that would allow him to switch the x-axis from Visit to Day. He wanted this so he could view group means by day. We discussed this and decided that the best approach would be to define the mean or median study day within each visit and plot that on a linear axis. 

Jeremy suggested making this a "title on the visit tick marks that is shown on mouseover instead of a separate continuous axis option - keeps the design (and coding) a lot simpler, but gives jack the  info he needs.  "

issues.title: Improved precision on tooltip means
issues.body:
Request from Jack:

Jack needs a higher level of precision on the means of certain measures (e.g., 2 decimal places). The current mean value in the tool-tip view is rounding too high, and doesn’t have adequate precision to answer the questions he is asking.  

Replicate for yourself here: http://interactive.it.rhoworld.com/dev/safety-explorers/studies/sunovion-sep360-311/#results-over-time with “LB – Hematocrit” as the Measure).  

# Test notes
* Verify that the box/violin plot tooltips display the summary statistics to a meaningful precision.
  * _Min_ and _Max_ should have the lowest precision.
  * _5th %_, _Q1_, _Median_, _Q3_, _95th %_, and _Mean_ should have precision to one more decimal place than the lowest precision.
  * _StDev_ should have precision to two more decimal places than the lowest precision.

This release adds data-driven ordering to the visits shown on the x-axis.

issues.title: Handle unscheduled visits systematically
issues.body:
# Description
Depending on how unscheduled visits are displayed on the x-axis, the chart can have some unintended behavior.

(See related issue for Outlier Explorer: https://github.com/RhoInc/safety-outlier-explorer/issues/68)

If visits are displayed purely chronologically, the challenge is that you end up creating a new event type that shows up in the middle of the data, but for only a small number of data points.  See example of visits 2(UN) and 5(UN) below:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10886203/34954676-5090adee-f9ef-11e7-821a-58163d33ee09.png)

Our primary medical monitor user has proposed that to fix this, we sort all Unscheduled visits to the far right end of the chart, where they are still visible, but they don't interfere with seeing the data flow through expected visits.

Proposed solutions:
1. Sort all unscheduled visits to the far right end of the chart, where they are still visible but they don't interfere with seeing the data flow through expected visits.
2. Retain visits in numerical order, but create a toggle that lets the user "Hide unscheduled visits"

# Test notes
Test out the new "Visits without data" and "Unscheduled visits" controls in CAT with the `safetyData/ADBDS.csv` data file (*not* `safetyData-queries/ADBDS.csv`). 

Confirm that:
- Unscheduled Visits and Visits with no data are shown/hidden when the toggle changes. 
- Change measure to "Alkaline Phosphatase (ALP)" and confirm that visits with no data are shown/hidden when the toggle changes.
- Test with the above with groups active (settings: `{groups:["RACE"]}`)
- Unscheduled visits are shown on initial load with `{"unscheduled_visits":true}` 
- Visits with no data are shown on initial load with `{"visits_without_data": true}`
- Only the visits are hidden/shown when explicitly specified using `{unscheduled_visit_values:["Unscheduled 2.1","Screening"]}`

issues.title: Make axes ranges stay consistent when using a filter
issues.body:
From Meagan Spychala on 9/19:

"It would be really useful if the axes’ ranges stayed consistent when using a filter.  For example, we were looking at a longitudinal graphic of systolic blood pressure across several sites, but each site’s graphic had an updated vertical range to fit that site, it did  the use aggregate of the data (i.e. if the SBP for the study as a whole was 70 to 160, but a site’s range was 90-120, the 90-120 would be the vertical axis range for that site only) .  Because the range of the vertical (SBP) and horizontal (Visit) axes can change, it is harder to see if the sites were in line with each other or if there was an outlying site.  I think it’s appropriate to have the range of the axes change depending on the measure (for example, SBP vs. DBP), but once you pick a measure, the axes’ range should be held constant based upon the overall data to be able to identify potential trends."
